<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880609-0022 </DOCNO><HL> Gambling Panel Endorses Casino Proposal in Detroit </HL><SO> </SO><IN> CNO </IN><DATELINE> DETROIT  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mayor Coleman Young's special gambling commission voted 46-15 in favor of plans to build as many as 12 casinos in the city.    The commission's endorsement of using gambling to pump up Detroit's economy was widely expected, and serves mainly to push the heated Detroit casino debate back to the city council.    Mayor Young is expected to ask the council to put the casino issue on the August primary ballot.    Detroit voters have rejected casinos twice before, despite projections of thousands of new jobs and millions in new tax revenue.    Gambling critics contend casinos would breed crime. Gambling would require the approval of the Michigan legislature. </TEXT></DOC>